ption of what it means to be American: the myths of the Frontier, the Founding, the Civil War (which he breaks into two opposing camps, Emancipation and the Lost Cause), and the Good War, embodied by the multiethnic platoon fighting for freedom. His argument is that while Trump and his MAGA followers have played up a frontier-inspired hostility to the federal government and rallied around Confederate symbols to champion a racially exclusive definition of American nationality, Blue America, taking its cue from the protest movements of the 1960s, envisions a limitlessly pluralistic country in which the federal government is the ultimate enforcer of rights and opportunities. American history—and the foundations of our democracy—have become a battleground. It is not clear at this time which vision will prevail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCulture conflictzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMythxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 21st Century.2bisacsh  a2020 election.  ablack lives matter.  achristian.  acivil rights.  acovid 19 pandemic.  ademocracy.  afascism.  agun rights.  ahealth care.  ahispanic.  aimmigration.  aindigenous.  aindustrialization.  ajanuary 6.  anative.  anew deal.  aobama.  apopulism.  arace.  avietnam.  avigilantism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074971740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674297036?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674297036423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674297036/original  a978-3-11-074971-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles